ce:section.ce:para:
The relevant physical quantities of hole-electron distribution including charge transfer distance (D), separation degree (t), overlap degree (Sr
                        ), and charge transfer number (CT) are presented in Table 1
                        . When the solvent is the same, the electron-donating ability of surface functional groups affects the charge transfer distance and overlap degree. For the dimethylamino- and amino-modified anthracene structures, both the charge transfer distances are greater than 2.5 Å. Among the three functional groups, the electron-donating ability of hydroxyl is the weakest, thus the charge transfer distance of hydroxyl-modified anthracene is less than 1.8 Å, and its hole-electron overlap degree is also the largest. For the same CD, as the polarity of the solvent increases, both D and CT show an increasing trend, and the high-polar MA solvent leads to the greatest degree of charge transfer of CDs. The results demonstrate that the electron-donating ability of the functional groups will affect the solvent effect. The stronger the electron-donating ability of the functional group, the more striking the solvent effect, and the greater shift the fluorescence emission of CD.
